<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_inertia-challenge" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Challenge - Moments of Inertia</title>

	<!--
	If you want an A*R*C*S (Analyze-Represent-Calculate-Sensemake) activity, use the <project> tag.
	If you want an Explain activity, use the <investigation> tag.
		Use this text for qualitative comparisons: <em>greater than</em>, <em>less than</em>, or <em>equal to</em>
	If you want a Calculate activity, use the <exploration> tag.
	-->

	<subsubsection>
	<title>A*R*C*S Activities</title>
	</subsubsection>

	<project xml:id="psa_rot-05">
        <title>The Cheese Slice</title>
		<statement><p></p>
		    <p>You have a one-dimensional slice of cheese with total mass <m>M</m> and total length <m>L</m>.  You know the linear mass density is <m>\lambda(x) = k \sqrt{x}</m>.  Find the constant of proportionality <m>k</m> (including its units) and the center of mass of the slice of cheese.</p>
		<assemblage>
		    <p>
				<alert><!--REPLACE_TAG-->Tip:</alert> For your representation (part 1c), sketch and label a physical diagram showing at least one small piece of the cheese slice.
			</p>
		</assemblage>
		<assemblage>
		    <p><alert><!--REPLACE_TAG-->Tip:</alert> For your numerical sensemaking (part 3b), sketch a graph of the mass density vs. <m>x</m> and use it to support a qualitative explanation for why the center of mass is located where it is relative to the geometric center of the cheese slice.
			</p>
		</assemblage>
		</statement>
	</project>



		<project xml:id="psa_rot-06">
        <title>The Cube I</title>
		<statement><p></p>
		    <p>A wooden cube with side length <m>L</m> and total mass <m>M</m> is rotating about an axis passing through one of its edges.  Use an integral to calculate the moment of inertia.</p>
		</statement>
		<assemblage>
		    <p><alert><!--REPLACE_TAG-->Tip:</alert> For your numerical sensemaking (part 3b), compare your symbolic expression to the moment of inertia expressions for other objects to help interpret the coefficient.
			</p>
		</assemblage>
	</project>

	<subsubsection>
	<title>Explanation Tasks</title>
		</subsubsection>

	<investigation xml:id="psa_rot-07">
        <title>The Cube II</title>
		<statement><p></p>
		    <p>The cube from the previous activity is instead rotating about an axis passing through its center (and through the center of one of its faces).  The parallel axis theorem can be used to demonstrate that the moment of inertia about this axis is smaller than the moment of inertia about the axis in the previous activity.  Give a qualitative explanation accounting for this result.</p>
		</statement>
	</investigation>

<subsubsection>
		<title>Metacognitive Reflection</title>
		</subsubsection>

		<activity>
			<title>When to Calculate</title>
			<p>
				
			</p>
			<p>
				You have now learned several ways to calculate moments of inertia: looking it up in a table, using the Parallel Axis Theorem, and using Chop-Multiply-Add to construct and integral directly.  When do you think each of these three methods is the <em>best</em> method to choose?  Give an example of an activity you have done highlighting the best use of each method.
			</p>
		</activity>


	
  
	
</section>

